# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aeg-german-company
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:aeg-german-company/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] A variety of largely proprietary gauges were devised for the numerous camera and projection systems being developed independently in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, along with various film feeding systems.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This resulted in cameras, projectors, and other equipment having to be calibrated to each gauge.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The 35 mm width, originally specified as 1+3⁄8 inches, was introduced around 1890 by William Kennedy Dickson and Thomas Edison, using film stock supplied by George Eastman.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Film 35 mm wide with four perforations per frame became accepted as the international standard gauge in 1909, and remained by far the dominant film gauge for image origination and projection until the advent of digital photography and cinematography.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The gauge has been versatile in application.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] It has been modified to include sound, redesigned to create a safer film base, formulated to capture color, has accommodated a bevy of widescreen formats, and has incorporated digital sound data into nearly all of its non-frame areas.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Eastman Kodak, Fujifilm and Agfa-Gevaert are some companies that offered 35 mm films.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] As of 2015, Kodak is the last remaining manufacturer of motion picture film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The ubiquity of 35 mm movie projectors in commercial movie theaters made 35 mm the only motion picture format that could be played in almost any cinema in the world, until digital projection largely superseded it.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1880, George Eastman began to manufacture gelatin dry photographic plates in Rochester, New York.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Walker, Eastman invented a holder for a roll of picture-carrying gelatin layer-coated paper.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Hannibal Goodwin then invented a nitrocellulose film base in 1887, the first transparent, flexible film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Eastman also produced these components, and his was the first major company to mass-produce such film when, in 1889, Eastman realized that the dry-gelatino-bromide emulsion could be coated onto this clear base, eliminating the paper.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] With the advent of flexible film, Thomas Edison quickly set out on his invention, the Kinetoscope, which was first shown at the Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences on May 9, 1893.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The Kinetoscope was a film loop system intended for one-person viewing.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Edison, along with assistant William Kennedy Dickson, followed that up with the Kinetophone, which combined the Kinetoscope with Edison's cylinder phonograph.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Beginning in March 1892, Eastman and then, from April 1893 into 1896, New York's Blair Camera Co. supplied Edison with film stock.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Edison's aperture defined a single frame of film at four perforations high.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Around 1896, a 35 mm projector known as a "photo-rotoscope" was made by W.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Hughes in London, which advanced the film by means of a "dog" motion.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] A court judgment in March 1902 invalidated Edison's claim, allowing any producer or distributor to use the Edison 35 mm film design without license.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Filmmakers were already doing so in Britain and Europe, where Edison did not file patents.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] At the time, film stock was usually supplied unperforated and punched by the filmmaker to their standards with perforation equipment.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] A variation developed by the Lumière brothers used a single circular perforation on each side of the frame towards the middle of the horizontal axis.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] When films began to be projected, several projection devices were unsuccessful and fell into obscurity because of technical failure, lack of business acumen on the part of their promoters, or both.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The Vitascope, the first projection device to use 35 mm, was technologically superior and compatible with the many motion pictures produced on 35 mm film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] When film editing was done by physically cutting the film, editing the picture could only have been done on the frame line.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] However, the sound was stored for the whole frame between each of the four sprocket holes, and so the sound editors could cut on any arbitrary set of holes, and thus get +1⁄4-frame edit resolution.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Three different digital soundtrack systems for 35 mm cinema release prints were introduced during the 1990s.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Because these soundtrack systems appear on different parts of the film, one movie can contain all of them, allowing broad distribution without regard for the sound system installed at individual theatres.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The analogue optical track technology has also changed: in the early years of the 21st century, distributors changed to using cyan dye optical soundtracks instead of applicated tracks, which use environmentally unfriendly chemicals to retain a silver (black-and-white) soundtrack.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Because traditional incandescent exciter lamps produce copious amounts of infrared light, and cyan tracks do not absorb infrared light, this change has required theaters to replace the incandescent exciter lamp with a complementary colored red LED or laser.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] These LED or laser exciters are backwards-compatible with older tracks.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The film *Anything Else* (2003) was the first to be released with only cyan tracks.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] To facilitate this changeover, intermediate prints known as "high magenta" prints were distributed.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] These prints used a silver plus dye soundtrack that were printed into the magenta dye layer.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The advantage gained was an optical soundtrack, with low levels of sibilant (cross-modulation) distortion, on both types of sound heads.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The success of digitally projected 3D movies in the first two decades of the 21st century led to a demand from some theater owners to be able to show these movies in 3D without incurring the high capital cost of installing digital projection equipment.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] To satisfy that demand, a number of systems had been proposed for 3D systems based on 35 mm film by Technicolor, Panavision and others.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] These systems are improved versions of the "over-under" stereo 3D prints first introduced in the 1960s.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] To be attractive to exhibitors, these schemes offered 3D films that can be projected by a standard 35 mm cinema projector with minimal modification, and so they are based on the use of "over-under" film prints.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In these prints a left-right pair of 2.39:1 non-anamorphic images are substituted for the one 2.39:1 anamorphic image of a 2D "scope" print.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The frame dimensions are based on those of the Techniscope 2-perf camera format used in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] However, when used for 3D the left and right frames are pulled down together, thus the standard 4-perf pulldown is retained, minimising the need for modifications to the projector or to long-play systems.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The linear speed of film through the projector and sound playback both remain exactly the same as in normal 2D operation.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The Technicolor system uses the polarisation of light to separate the left and right eye images and for this they rent to exhibitors a combination splitter-polarizer-lens assembly which can be fitted to a lens turret in the same manner as an anamorphic lens.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In contrast, the Panavision system uses a spectral comb filter system, but their combination splitter-filter-lens is physically similar to the Technicolor assembly and can be used in the same way.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] No other modifications are required to the projector for either system, though for the Technicolor system a silver screen is necessary, as it would be with polarised-light digital 3D.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Thus a programme can readily include both 2D and 3D segments with only the lens needing to be changed between them.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In June 2012, Panavision 3D systems for both 35 mm film and digital projection were withdrawn from the market by DVPO theatrical (who marketed these system on behalf of Panavision) citing "challenging global economic and 3D market conditions".
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In the transition period centered around 2010–2015, the rapid conversion of the cinema exhibition industry to digital projection saw 35 mm film projectors removed from most of the projection rooms as they were replaced by digital projectors.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] By the mid-2010s, most of the theaters across the world had been converted to digital projection, although a small percentage (under 10% overall) continued running 35 mm projectors, mostly indie theaters or those in more economically challenged regions.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] However, it continued as a niche market for enthusiasts and format lovers.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In the 2020s, 35 mm has seen some resurgence in usage.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The resurgence comes from those who find 35 mm to be more visually pleasing and evoke nostalgic feelings, as well as a desire from millennial and Generation Z filmmakers and photographers to preserve the art.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Several films such as *Marty Supreme* and *Anora* have been produced using 35 mm film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In an effort to rebuild business lost during the COVID-19 pandemic, some theaters have used special event screenings of films with 35 mm film projectors to attract customers.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Most of these screenings occur in large metropolitan areas.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Originally, film was a strip of cellulose nitrate coated with black-and-white photographic emulsion.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Griffith, color tinted or toned portions of their movies for dramatic impact, and by 1920, 80 to 90 percent of all films were tinted.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The first successful natural color process was Britain's Kinemacolor (1909–1915), a two-color additive process that used a rotating disk with red and green filters in front of the camera lens and the projector lens.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] But any process that photographed and projected the colors sequentially was subject to color "fringing" around moving objects, and a general color flickering.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1916, William Van Doren Kelley began developing Prizma, the first commercially viable American color process using 35 mm film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Initially, like Kinemacolor, it photographed the color elements one after the other and projected the results by additive synthesis.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Ultimately, Prizma was refined to bipack photography, with two strips of film, one treated to be sensitive to red and the other not, running through the camera face to face.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This system of two-color bipack photography and two-sided prints was the basis for many later color processes, such as Multicolor, Brewster Color and Cinecolor.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Although it had been available previously, color in Hollywood feature films first became truly practical from the studios' commercial perspective with the advent of Technicolor, whose main advantage was quality prints in less time than its competitors.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In its earliest incarnations, Technicolor was another two-color system that could reproduce a range of reds, muted bluish greens, pinks, browns, tans and grays, but not real blues or yellows.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] *The Toll of the Sea*, released in 1922, was the first film printed in their subtractive color system.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Technicolor's camera photographed each pair of color-filtered frames simultaneously on one strip of black-and-white film by means of a beam splitter prism behind the camera lens.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Two prints on half-thickness stock were made from the negative, one from only the red-filtered frames, the other from the green-filtered frames.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] After development, the silver images on the prints were chemically toned to convert them into images of the approximately complementary colors.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The two strips were then cemented together back to back, forming a single strip similar to duplitized film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1928, Technicolor started making their prints by the imbibition process, which was mechanical rather than photographic and allowed the color components to be combined on the same side of the film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Using two matrix films bearing hardened gelatin relief images, thicker where the image was darker, aniline color dyes were transferred into the gelatin coating on a third, blank strip of film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Technicolor re-emerged as a three-color process for cartoons in 1932 and live action in 1934.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Using a different arrangement of a beam-splitter cube and color filters behind the lens, the camera simultaneously exposed three individual strips of black-and-white film, each one recording one-third of the spectrum, which allowed virtually the entire spectrum of colors to be reproduced.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] A printing matrix with a hardened gelatin relief image was made from each negative, and the three matrices transferred color dyes into a blank film to create the print.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Two-color processes, however, were far from extinct.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Gundelfinger revived the Multicolor process under the company name Cinecolor.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Cinecolor saw considerable use in animation and low-budget pictures, mainly because it cost much less than three-color Technicolor.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] If color design was carefully managed, the lack of colors such as true green could pass unnoticed.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Although Cinecolor used the same duplitized stock as Prizma and Multicolor, it had the advantage that its printing and processing methods yielded larger quantities of finished film in less time.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1950, Kodak announced the first Eastman color 35 mm negative film (along with a complementary positive film) that could record all three primary colors on the same strip of film.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] An improved version in 1952 was quickly adopted by Hollywood, making the use of three-strip Technicolor cameras and bipack cameras (used in two-color systems such as Cinecolor) obsolete in color cinematography.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This "monopack" structure is made up of three separate emulsion layers, one sensitive to red light, one to green and one to blue.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Although Eastman Kodak had first introduced acetate-based film, it was far too brittle and prone to shrinkage, so the dangerously flammable nitrate-based cellulose films were generally used for motion picture camera and print films.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1949 Kodak began replacing all nitrocellulose (nitrate-based) films with the safer, more robust cellulose triacetate-based "Safety" films.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1950 the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences awarded Kodak with a Scientific and Technical Academy Award (Oscar) for the safer triacetate stock.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] By 1952, all camera and projector films were triacetate-based.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Most if not all film prints today are made from synthetic polyester safety base (which started replacing Triacetate film for prints in the early 1990s).
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The downside of polyester film is that it is extremely strong, and, in case of a fault, will stretch and not break–potentially causing damage to the projector and ruining a fairly large stretch of film: 2–3 ft or approximately 2 seconds.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Also, polyester film will melt if exposed to the projector lamp for too long.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Polyester films are not compatible with solvent-based assembly processes.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Besides black & white and color negative films, there are black & white and color reversal films, which when developed create a positive ("natural") image that is projectable.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] There are also films sensitive to non-visible wavelengths of light, such as infrared.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In the conventional motion picture format, frames are four perforations tall, with an aspect ratio of 1.375:1, 22 by 16 mm (0.866 by 0.630 in).
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This is a derivation of the aspect ratio and frame size designated by Thomas Edison (24.89 by 18.67 millimetres or 0.980 by 0.735 inches) at the dawn of motion pictures, which was an aspect ratio of 1.33:1.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The first sound features were released in 1926–27, and while Warner Bros. was using synchronized phonograph discs (sound-on-disc), Fox placed the soundtrack in an optical record directly on the film (sound-on-film) on a strip between the sprocket holes and the image frame.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] "Sound-on-film" was soon adopted by the other Hollywood studios, resulting in an almost square image ratio of 0.860 in by 0.820 in.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] By 1929, most movie studios had revamped this format using their own house aperture plate size to try to recreate the older screen ratio of 1.33:1.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Furthermore, every theater chain had their own house aperture plate size in which the picture was projected.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] These sizes often did not match up even between theaters and studios owned by the same company, and therefore, uneven projection practices occurred.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In November 1929, the Society of Motion Picture Engineers set a standard aperture ratio of 0.800 in by 0.600 in.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Known as the "1930 standard", studios which followed the suggested practice of marking their camera viewfinders for this ratio were: Paramount-Famous-Lasky, Metro-Goldwyn Mayer, United Artists, Pathe, Universal, RKO, Tiffany-Stahl, Mack Sennett, Darmour, and Educational.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The Fox Studio markings were the same width but allowed .04 in more height.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1932, in refining this ratio, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences expanded upon this 1930 standard.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The camera aperture became 22 by 16 mm (0.87 by 0.63 in), and the projected image would use an aperture plate size of 0.825 by 0.600 in (21.0 by 15.2 mm), yielding an aspect ratio of 1.375:1.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This became known as the "Academy" ratio.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Since the 1950s the aspect ratio of some theatrically released motion picture films has been 1.85:1 (1.66:1 in Europe) or 2.35:1 (2.40:1 after 1970).
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The image area for "TV transmission" is slightly smaller than the full "Academy" ratio at 21 by 16 mm (0.83 by 0.63 in), an aspect ratio of 1.33:1.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Hence when the "Academy" ratio is referred to as having an aspect ratio of 1.33:1, it is done so mistakenly.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The commonly used anamorphic format uses a similar four-perf frame, but an anamorphic lens is used on the camera and projector to produce a wider image, today with an aspect ratio of about 2.39:1 (more commonly referred to as 2.40:1).
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The ratio was formerly 2.35:1—and is still often mistakenly referred to as such—until an SMPTE revision of projection standards in 1970.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The image, as recorded on the negative and print, is horizontally compressed (squeezed) by a factor of 2.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The unexpected success of the Cinerama widescreen process in 1952 led to a boom in film format innovations to compete with the growing audiences of television and the dwindling audiences in movie theaters.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] These processes could give theatergoers an experience that television could not at that time—color, stereophonic sound and panoramic vision.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Before the end of the year, 20th Century Fox had narrowly "won" a race to obtain an anamorphic optical system invented by Henri Chrétien, and soon began promoting the Cinemascope technology as early as the production phase.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Paramount Pictures began this trend with their aspect ratio of 1.66:1, first used in *Shane*, which was originally shot for Academy ratio.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] It was Universal Studios, however, with their May release of *Thunder Bay* that introduced the now standard 1.85:1 format to American audiences and brought attention to the industry the capability and low cost of equipping theaters for this transition.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Other studios followed suit with aspect ratios of 1.75:1 up to 2:1.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] For a time, these various ratios were used by different studios in different productions, but by 1956, the aspect ratio of 1.85:1 became the "standard" US format.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] These *flat* films are photographed with the full Academy frame, but are matted (most often with a mask in the theater projector, not in the camera) to obtain the "wide" aspect ratio.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The standard, in some European countries, became 1.66:1 instead of 1.85:1, although some productions with pre-determined American distributors composed for the latter to appeal to US markets.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In September 1953, 20th Century Fox debuted CinemaScope with their production of *The Robe* to great success.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] CinemaScope became the first marketable usage of an anamorphic widescreen process and became the basis for a host of "formats", usually suffixed with *-scope,* that were otherwise identical in specification, although sometimes inferior in optical quality.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The 1950s and 1960s saw many other novel processes using 35 mm, such as VistaVision, SuperScope, and Technirama, most of which ultimately became obsolete.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] VistaVision, however, would be revived decades later by Lucasfilm and other studios for special effects work, while a SuperScope variant became the predecessor to the modern Super 35 format that is popular today.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The concept behind Super 35 originated with the Tushinsky Brothers' SuperScope format, particularly the SuperScope 235 specification from 1956.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1982, Joe Dunton revived the format for *Dance Craze*, and Technicolor soon marketed it under the name "Super Techniscope" before the industry settled on the name Super 35.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The cropped frame is then converted at the intermediate stage to a 4-perf anamorphically squeezed print compatible with the anamorphic projection standard.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This allows an "anamorphic" frame to be captured with non-anamorphic lenses, which are much more common.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Until the year 2000, once the film was photographed in Super 35, an optical printer was used to anamorphose (squeeze) the image.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This optical step reduced the overall quality of the image and made Super 35 a controversial subject among cinematographers, many who preferred the higher image quality and frame negative area of anamorphic photography (especially with regard to granularity).
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The non-anamorphic widescreen ratios (most commonly 1.85:1) used in modern feature films makes inefficient use of the available image area on 35 mm film using the standard 4-perf pulldown; the height of a 1.85:1 frame occupying only 65% of the distance between the frames.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] It is clear, therefore, that a change to a 3-perf pulldown would allow for a 25% reduction in film consumption whilst still accommodating the full 1.85:1 frame.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Ever since the introduction of these widescreen formats in the 1950s various film directors and cinematographers have argued in favour of the industry making such a change.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The Canadian cinematographer Miklos Lente invented and patented a three-perforation pull down system which he called "Trilent 35" in 1975 though he was unable to persuade the industry to adopt it.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The idea was later taken up by the Swedish film-maker Rune Ericson who was a strong advocate for the 3-perf system.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Ericson shot his 51st feature *Pirates of the Lake* in 1986 using two Panaflex cameras modified to 3-perf pulldown and suggested that the industry could change over completely over the course of ten-years.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] However, the movie industry did not make the change mainly because it would have required the modification of the thousands of existing 35 mm projectors in movie theaters all over the world.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Whilst it would have been possible to shoot in 3-perf and then convert to standard 4-perf for release prints the extra complications this would cause and the additional optical printing stage required made this an unattractive option at the time for most film makers.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] However, in television production, where compatibility with an installed base of 35 mm film projectors is unnecessary, the 3-perf format is sometimes used, giving—if used with Super 35—the 16:9 ratio used by HDTV and reducing film usage by 25 percent.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Because of 3-perf's incompatibility with standard 4-perf equipment, it can utilize the whole negative area between the perforations (Super 35) without worrying about compatibility with existing equipment; the Super 35 image area includes what would be the soundtrack area in a standard print.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] All 3-perf negatives require optical or digital conversion to standard 4-perf if a film print is desired, though 3-perf can easily be transferred to video with little to no difficulty by modern telecine or film scanners.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] With digital intermediate now a standard process for feature film post-production, 3-perf is becoming increasingly popular for feature film productions which would otherwise be averse to an optical conversion stage.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The VistaVision motion picture format was created in 1954 by Paramount Pictures to create a finer-grained negative and print for flat widescreen films.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Similar to still photography, the format uses a camera running 35 mm film horizontally instead of vertically through the camera, with frames that are eight perforations long, resulting in a wider aspect ratio of 1.5:1 and greater detail, as more of the negative area is used per frame.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This format is unprojectable in standard theaters and requires an optical step to reduce the image into the standard 4-perf vertical 35 mm frame.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Its usage has again declined since the dominance of computer-based visual effects, although it still sees limited utilization.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Film perforations were originally round holes cut into the side of the film, but as these perforations were subject to wear and deformation, the shape was changed to what is now called the Bell & Howell (BH) perforation, which has straight top and bottom edges and outward curving sides.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The BH perforation's dimensions are 0.110 inches (2.8 mm) from the middle of the side curve to opposite top corner by 0.073 inches (1.9 mm) in height.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The BH1866 perforation, or BH perforation with a pitch of 0.1866 inches (4.74 mm), is the modern standard for negative and internegative films.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Because BH has sharp corners, the repeated use of the film through intermittent movement projectors creates strain that can easily tear the perforations.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Furthermore, they tended to shrink as the print slowly decayed.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Therefore, larger perforations with a rectangular base and rounded corners were introduced by Kodak in 1924 to improve steadiness, registration, durability, and longevity.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The increased height also means that the image registration was considerably less accurate than BH perfs, which remains the standard for negatives.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The KS1870 perforation, or KS perforation with a pitch of 0.1870 inches (4.75 mm), is the modern standard for release prints.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] These two perforations have remained by far the most commonly used ones.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] BH perforations are also known as *N* (negative) and KS as *P* (positive).
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The Bell & Howell perf remains the standard for camera negative films because of its perforation dimensions in comparison to most printers, thus it can keep a steady image compared to other perforations.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The Dubray–Howell (DH) perforation was first proposed in 1932 to replace the two perfs with a single hybrid.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The proposed standard was, like KS, rectangular with rounded corners and a width of 0.1100 inches (2.79 mm), and, like BH, was 0.073 inches (1.9 mm) tall.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] This gave it longer projection life but also improved registration.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] One of its primary applications was usage in Technicolor's dye imbibition printing (dye transfer).
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The DH perf never had broad uptake, and Kodak's introduction of monopack Eastmancolor film in the 1950s reduced the demand for dye transfer, although the DH perforation persists in special application intermediate films.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] In 1953, the introduction of CinemaScope by Fox Studios required the creation of a different shape of perforation which was nearly square and smaller to provide space for four magnetic sound stripes for stereophonic and surround sound.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] These perforations are commonly referred to as CinemaScope (CS) or "Fox hole" perfs.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Their dimensions are 0.0780 inches (1.98 mm) in width by 0.0730 inches (1.85 mm) in height.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Due to the size difference, CS perfed film cannot be run through a projector with standard KS sprocket teeth, but KS prints *can* be run on sprockets with CS teeth.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Shrunken film with KS prints that would normally be damaged in a projector with KS sprockets may sometimes be run far more gently through a projector with CS sprockets because of the smaller size of the teeth.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Magnetic striped 35 mm film became obsolete in the 1980s after the advent of Dolby Stereo, as a result film with CS perfs is no longer manufactured.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] During continuous contact printing, the raw stock and the negative are placed next to one another around the sprocket wheel of the printer.
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] The negative, which is the closer of the two to the sprocket wheel (thus creating a slightly shorter path), must have a marginally shorter pitch between perforations (0.1866 in pitch); the raw stock has a long pitch (0.1870 in).
[src:aeg-german-company/35-mm-movie-film] Technical specifications for 35 mm film are standardized by SMPTE.
[src:aeg-german-company/aag-1900-automobile] The trademark for the name was registered on 28 November 1899 and registered on 8 February 1900.
[src:aeg-german-company/aag-1900-automobile] The company factory was bought by the politician Emil Rathenau, also the head of the AEG Group.
[src:aeg-german-company/aag-1900-automobile] He renamed it to the Neue Automobil Gesellschaft (NAG for short), and the company produced cars until 1934.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Adtranz manufactured locomotives, high-speed, regional, metro and underground passenger trains, trams and people movers as well as freight wagons.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Non-rolling stock businesses included railway electrification and signalling infrastructure.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] On 8 May 1995, ABB and Daimler-Benz proposed a merger of their rail industry-related activities into a single autonomous 50:50 joint venture; the combined group would be the largest rail-technology company in the world.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] In Germany the combined company, along with Siemens would have a duopoly or near-duopoly in the market areas of electric locomotives, mainline and regional electric and diesel multiple units, trams and metros, and catenary systems.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] In the EU, outside Germany, the merger would have meant no significant market share increase, including Scandinavia, where ABB had a dominant market share.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The proposed merger was approved by government regulators on 18 October 1995, on the condition that both companies divest themselves of any shares in Kiepe, a traction components company.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The merger came into force on 1 January 1996.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The company's manufacturing facilities and product lines were rationalised, including a standard form of car body; after 18 months manufacturing costs had been reduced by 30%, revenues and orders also rose from 1996 to 1997.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] However the company continued to lose money, $111 million in 1997.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Polish manufacturer Pafawag was acquired in 1997 and the facility modernised, controlling interests in *MÁV Dunakeszi*, Hungary and *Schindler Waggon* Switzerland were also acquired by the end of 1997.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] A new diesel locomotive design with engine and electrical traction system provided by General Electric was introduced, named "Blue Tiger".
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Adtranz intended to consolidate its product range around these families once on-going deliveries were finished.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Adtranz continued operating at a loss in 1998, attributed to earlier contracts with underestimated costs, as well as technical problems with products, in spite of an order for 400 locomotives from Deutsche Bahn, necessitating the acquisition of Swiss Locomotive and Machine Works.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] In January 1999, ABB sold its 50% stake in Adtranz to DaimlerChrysler for $472 million, taking up a previous agreement made on the formation of the joint venture whereby DaimlerChrysler was required to purchase ABB's stake.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Adtranz finally achieved profitability in 2000, as DaimlerChrysler prepared to sell off Adtranz.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The Greenbrier Companies acquired the freight wagon manufacturing business in January 2000.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The overhead electrification systems installations business was sold to Balfour Beatty in late 2000 for €153 million.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] No buyer was found for the railway signalling division.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The remaining assets of Adtranz were sold to Bombardier, in a $711 million deal announced in August 2000, a price considered to be low by industry analysts.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The sale was cleared by the European Union in April 2001 on the condition that Bombardier would license or sell the Adtranz regional train and tram products to Stadler Rail in the German market, due to the large market share of Bombardier and Adtranz in the country.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The deal would make Stadler a viable independent company providing competition to Bombardier.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The takeover came into legal effect on 1 May 2001 with a final price of $725 million and ADtranz was folded into the Bombardier Transportation division.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Within months of the sale, Bombardier said that it was misled about the financial situation of Adtranz.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Bombardier sued DaimlerChrysler for providing misleading financial information.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The companies settled in September 2004 with DaimlerChrysler agreeing to refund $209 million, making the final sale price for Adtranz just $516 million.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The brand *Adtranz* was created by Landor Associates as part of the corporate identity of ***A**BB **D**aimler Ben**z** **Tran**sportation*.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] It is an acronym derived from selected letters of the complete name of the first company using it: *A*BB *D*aimler-Benz *Trans*portation, with a *z* in place of an *s* at the end for the name to imply a complete product platform from A to Z.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] It was capitalised by the companies with a capital *D* as *ADtranz*, following the standard English text formatting and capitalisation rules it is spelled with a small *d* as *Adtranz*.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Above the text *ADtranz*, the company logo included a green dot, symbolising a signal set on green, as well as the environmental friendliness of railways.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] The company also registered the slogan *ADtranz – we speak railways*.
[src:aeg-german-company/adtranz] Rights on the brand and slogan were deleted in 2008 and 2007 respectively.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-brand] Founded in 1887, it originally belonged to the German company of the same name, active in the electronics and metalworking sectors.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-brand] In 1994, the household appliances division was sold to the Swedish company Electrolux, which still owns it and sells products under the brand name.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-brand] The AEG brand was born in 1887 following the name change of the company founded in 1883.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-brand] In 1985, AEG was acquired by Daimler-Benz, into which it was incorporated in 1996.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-brand] In 1994, AEG's household appliances division was sold to the Swedish multinational Electrolux, which relaunched the brand as AEG Electrolux in 2005.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The **AEG G.IV** was a biplane bomber aircraft designed and produced by the German aircraft manufacturer Allgemeine Elektrizitäts-Gesellschaft.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] It saw action during the First World War with the Luftstreitkräfte (Imperial German Army Air Service).
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The G.IV was developed from the AEG G.III, featuring various refinements to power, bomb-load, and dimensions; specifically, it featured double the bomb capacity of the AEG G.II.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Introduced to service during late 1916, the G.IV managed to achieve some operational success in both reconnaissance and direct combat missions.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Because of its relatively short range, the G.IV served mainly as a tactical bomber, thus it operated close to the front lines.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] It initially flew both day and night operations in France, Romania, Greece, and Italy, but was increasingly restricted to night missions as the conflict progressed.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Many night operations were considered nuisance raids, conducting without any specific targets other than the intention of disrupting enemy activity at night and achieving some collateral damage at best.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Some officials concluded that the G.IV was still inadequate in terms of offensive capacity and performance, thus further improvements were sought.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] A single specialised G.IV was converted into an armored, antitank gunship, the G.IVk (*Kanone*) with two 20 mm Becker cannon, but it did not see action.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The G.IV was the last in the series to see action, as while development of the improved G.V did proceed, the Armistice of 1918 that brought an end to the combat came into effect before this successor could become operational.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The *Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft* (AEG) G.IV was derived from the earlier G.III; according to the aviation historians Peter Gray and Owen Thetford, it was only a slight refinement of its predecessor.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Designed from the onset to operate as a tactical bomber, the designers opted to incorporate various relatively modern technologies of the era, including onboard radios and electrically heated suits for the crew.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Unlike the other German twin-engined *Großflugzeug*-class ("G") bombers, such as the Gotha G.V and the Friedrichshafen G.III, the G.IV featured an all-metal, welded-tube frame that made the aircraft considerably more durable than most of its contemporaries.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] This design choice resulted in a relatively high structural weight despite its compact size for a twin-engined aircraft.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The fuselage was constructed as one complete unit, instead of using subassemblies.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] In addition to the fuselage, the tail unit also made use of steel-tube construction.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Aside from plywood paneling on the nose, the exterior was covered by fabric.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The tail unit featured a particularly tall rudder, which necessitated unconventional bracing to the upper longeron; the tail fins also featured a relatively unorthodox high camber.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The G.IV was powered by a pair of Mercedes D.IVa six-cylinder, water-cooled, inline, piston engines; cooling was provided via automotive-type radiators positioned immediately aft of the propellers.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] These engines were mounted by a complex array of steel struts to the lower wing spars and braced against the upper longerons of the fuselage; somewhat unusually, no connecting struts were between the engine and the upper wing.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The wings comprised a fixed central section with detachable swept outer panels of composite construction, that being a pair of 50 mm diameter steel-tube spars and solid wood ribs.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] To lighten the wing structure, strategically placed holes were drilled, and besides loose threading, no solid connections between the ribs and the spars were made; several of the ribs were also false.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The upper wing featured large balanced ailerons that shared a similar profile to that of the AEG C.IV.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The undercarriage comprised a relatively sturdy tailskid and a pair of wheels, each one mounted directly beneath each engine and equipped with shock absorbers.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The G.IV was relatively well equipped in terms of armament, being capable of carrying a warload of 400 kg (880 lb).
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] At the port side of the rear cockpit were a pair of tracks for carrying 25 lb bombs, an additional bomb rack was fitted between the rear and forward cockpits underneath the floor.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Provisions for the carriage of up to five 50 lb bombs, one underneath each wing and up to three beneath the fuselage, were also made Bomb release was controlled from the forward cockpit.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The G.IV was typically flown by a three-man crew, although a fourth could be readily accommodated when required.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The rear gunner's cockpit was located on the top of the fuselage, being equipped with a hinged window in the floor for viewing and fending off pursuing aircraft.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] When suitably configured, dual flight controls (with the notable exception of the ailerons) could be furnished, although this facility was of limited use outside of emergencies.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Several experimental modifications were made to the G.IV.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] A version with increased span and three bay struts, the G.IVb, is known to have been built.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Furthermore, the aircraft was also converted into an armored, antitank gunship, the G.IVk (*Kanone*) with two 20 mm Becker cannon, but this model is believed to have never entered service.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The G.IV entered service with the German Air Force in late 1916.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Even at the start of its career, its performance in several metrics was inferior to that of contemporary Gothas, including range and payload capacity, despite typically sharing the same Mercedes D.IVa engine.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] However, while Gotha crews struggled to keep their heavy aircraft aloft, the G.IV was regarded as being a relatively easy aircraft to fly.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] In light of its relatively small payload when fully fueled, missions typically undertaken by the type were short range, thus permitting more munitions to be carried at the expense of fuel.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] On occasion, it was flown without any offensive payload to perform aerial reconnaissance flights.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The G.IV performed both day- and night-time bombing missions, often targeting areas to the rear of the contact line.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Some crews of *Kampfgeschwader* 4 are reputed to have flown up to seven combat missions per night on the Italian front.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] One notable mission conducted by a G.IV, piloted by Hauptmann Hermann Köhl, was conducted against the railway sheds in Padua, Italy.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] By August 1918, around 50 aircraft are believed to have been still active with the German Air Force.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The G.IV continued to be used operationally by Germans through to the Armistice of 11 November 1918 that ended the conflict.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Soon, the British Army of Occupation of the Rhineland took over.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] A single example (number 574/18) is preserved at the Canada Aviation and Space Museum.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] This example is significant not only as the only one of its kind in existence, but also as the only preserved German, twin-engined combat aircraft from the First World War.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] The aircraft was brought to Canada in 1919 as a war trophy and has been at the museum since 1970.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] Fitted with an increased span three-bay wing.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-g-iv] cannon, one in a dorsal mounting and one in a turret under the nose.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The company's initial focus was driven by electrical lighting, as in 1881, Rathenau had acquired the rights to the electric light bulb at the International Exposition of Electricity in Paris.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Using small power stations, his company introduced electrical lighting to cafés, restaurants, and theaters, despite the high costs and limitations.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] By the end of the 19th century, AEG had constructed 248 power stations, providing a total of 210,000 hp of electricity for lighting, tramways, and household devices.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] During the Second World War, AEG worked with the Nazi Party and benefited from forced labor in Nazi concentration camps.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] After the war, its headquarters moved to Frankfurt am Main.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1967, AEG joined with its subsidiary Telefunken.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1985, Daimler-Benz purchased AEG and wholly integrated the company in 1996.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The remains of AEG became part of Adtranz and Deutsche Aerospace.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] After acquiring the AEG household subsidiary AEG Hausgeräte in 1994, Electrolux obtained the rights to the AEG brand name in 2005, which it now uses on some of its products.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The AEG name is also licensed to various brand partners under the Electrolux Global Brand Licensing program.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1883, Emil Rathenau founded Deutsche Edison-Gesellschaft für angewandte Elektricität in Berlin.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1888, it was renamed as Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Initially producing electrical equipment (such as light bulbs, motors, and generators), the company soon became involved in AC electric-transmission systems.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1907, Peter Behrens was appointed as artistic consultant to AEG.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] This led to the creation of the company's initial corporate identity, with products and advertising sharing common design features.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The company expanded in the first half of the 20th century, and it is credited with a number of firsts and inventions in electrical engineering.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] During the same period, it entered the automobile and airplane markets.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Electrical equipment for railways was produced during this time, beginning a long history of supplying the German railways with electrical equipment.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] During the Second World War, AEG joined with other large companies such as IG Farben, Thyssen, and Krupp in their support of the Nazis.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The company benefited from the use of large numbers of forced labourers, as well as concentration-camp prisoners, under inhuman conditions of work.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] After WWII, the company lost its businesses in the eastern part of Germany.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] After a merger in 1967, the company was renamed Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft AEG-Telefunken, and from 1979 on, only as AEG-Telefunken.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The company experienced financial difficulties during the 1970s, resulting in the sale of some assets.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1983, the consumer electronics division Telefunken Fernseh und Rundfunk was sold.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1985, the company retook the name AEG and the remainder of the company was acquired by Daimler-Benz; the parts that remained were primarily related to electric power distribution and electric motor technology.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Under Daimler-Benz ownership, the former AEG companies eventually became part of the newly named Adtranz in 1995, and the AEG name was no longer used.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Electrolux, which had already acquired the household subsidiary AEG Hausgeräte in 1994, now own the rights to use and license the AEG brand.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The company originated in 1882, when Emil Rathenau acquired licences to use some of Thomas Edison's lamp patents in Germany.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The Deutsche Edison Gesellschaft ("German Edison Company") was founded in 1883 with the financial backing of banks and private individuals, with Emil Rathenau as company director.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1884, Munich-born engineer Oskar von Miller (who later founded Deutsches Museum) joined the executive board.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The same year, the company entered negotiations with the Berlin Magistrat (the municipal body) to supply electricity to a large area from a central supply, which resulted in the formation of the Städtischen Elektrizitätswerke (A.G.StEW) ("City electricity works company (Berlin)") on 8 May 1884.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The original factory was located near Stettiner Bahnhof.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1887, the company acquired land in the Berlin-Gesundbrunnen area on which the Weddingsche Maschinenfabrik (founded by Wilhelm Wedding) was previously located.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In the same year, in addition to a restructuring and expansion of the production range, the AEG name was adopted.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1887, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrowolsky joined the company as chief engineer, later becoming vice-director.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] His work on polyphase electric power led him to become the world's leading engineer in three-phase electric power systems at the end of the 1880s.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] This success marked one of beginnings of the general use of alternating current for electrification in Germany, and showed that distance transmission of electric power could be economically useful.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In the same year, the Stadtbahn Halle/Saale (City railway Halle–Saale) opened the first electric tram system (of notable size) in Germany.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Tropp Paul began his work for the AEG from 1889/90 until 1893, and Franz Schwechten designed the facades of the Acker- und Hussitenstraße in 1894–95.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1894, the site of the former Berlin Viehmarktgasse (cattle market alley) was purchased.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] This had a railroad siding connecting to the Berlin rail network, but no rail connection existed between the two plants.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1895, an underground railway link between the two plots was built in a tunnel 270 meters long.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The tunnel was built by Siemens & Halske under the direction of C.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Schwebel and Wilhelm Lauter, who were also connected in the building of what is now the Spree tunnel Stralau used by the U-Bahn.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] By 1889, AEG were known as specialists in the construction of industrial portable drilling machines, some of which were driven by flexible shafts from electric motors.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG also developed a toothed-belt drive to reduce motor speed down to that required by machine tools.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1903, the competing radio companies AEG and Siemens & Halske merged, forming a joint subsidiary named Telefunken.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1907, architect Peter Behrens became an artistic adviser.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Responsible for the design of all products, advertising, and architecture, he has since become considered as the world's first corporate designer.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Behren's philosophy was to create a building which is solid, strong and simple in its structure.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] It is perfect for doing its job of producing large, heavy machinery.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The dimensions of the building were chosen to allow turbines to be transported above other machinery.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In the 1920s, AEG became a global supplier of electrical know-how and equipment.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1923, for example, it provided most of the essential materials and a team of engineers to oversee the electrification of British-ruled Palestine.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] British firms, at the time, could not compete with the prices of AEG.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The activity of the company soon extended to all areas of electrical power engineering, including electric lighting, electric power, electric railways, and electrochemical plants, as well as the construction of steam turbines, automobiles, cables, and cable materials.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] On 20 June 1915, founder Emil Rathenau died at age 77.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG donated 60,000 Reichsmarks to the Nazi party after the Secret Meeting of 20 February 1933 at which the twin goals of complete power and national rearmament were explained by Hitler.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] They joined with other large companies, such as IG Farben, Thyssen and Krupp, in their support of the Nazis, especially in promoting re-armament of the Wehrmacht, Luftwaffe, and Kriegsmarine.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] During the war itself, they were to use large numbers of forced labourers as well as concentration camp prisoners, under inhuman conditions of work.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG worked extensively with the Nazi party in occupied Poland.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG was forced to relinquish Kabelwerk Krakow, a cable manufacturing plant, to the Nazi party.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Kabelwerk Krakow was located in Krakow-Plaszow and used forced Jewish labor manufacturing cables from 1942 to 1944.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1943, AEG began to relocate goods and evacuate workers.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Goods were relocated to various places, including Berlin and Sudetenland.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] When installing electric and lighting systems for the Waffen-SS training grounds in Dębica, AEG used forced labor from Jews placed in the Pustkow labor camp located in south east Poland.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] During World War II, an AEG factory near Riga used female slave labour.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG was also contracted for the production of electrical equipment at Auschwitz concentration camp.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] 36 at the new sub-camp of Auschwitz III and also known as Monowitz, called "Arbeitslager Blechhammer".
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Most of them would die in 1945 during the death marches and finally in Buchenwald.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG was a major supplier of grips for P38 pistols manufactured by Walther Arms, Mauser, as well as on the early wartime Spreewerk P38s.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In an effort to express regret for its use of Jewish slave labour in World War II, AEG joined with Rheinmetall, Siemens, Krupp, and I G Farben to pay DEM75 million in reparations to the Jewish Claims Conference.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The steam and electric locomotive plant in Hennigsdorf (Fabriken Hennigsdorf) became a Volkseigener Betrieb (VEB) (people owned enterprise) as the Lokomotivbau Elektrotechnische Werke (LEW) ("electric locomotive works").
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The cable plant (Draht-, Kabel- und Metallwerk Oberspree) and apparatus factory (Apparatefabrik Treptow) and other facilities also lay in East Germany and became Sowjetische Aktiengesellschaft (SAG) (Soviet joint-stock companies).
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Over 90% of assets in Berlin lay in the Russian occupied zone and were lost.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The headquarters for the non-expropriated parts of the company was moved first to Hamburg and then finally to Frankfurt am Main, the headquarters in Berlin having been destroyed.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1970, AEG-Telefunken had 178,000 employees worldwide, and was the 12th largest electrical company in the world.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The company was burdened by, among other things, unsuccessful projects such as an automated baggage conveyor system at Frankfurt Airport and nuclear powerplant construction.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In particular, the nuclear power plant at Würgassen, the commissioning of which was delayed by several years due to technical problems cost AEG hundreds of millions of DM.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] As a result, the company paid its last dividend in 1972.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The entertainment arm (Telefunken Fernseh und Rundfunk) headquartered in Hanover was sold.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] This was followed by the computer mainframe business (TR 4, TR 10, TR 440) (a partnership under the name Telefunken Computer with the company Nixdorf) was sold to Siemens.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The process computer (TR 84, TR 86, AEG 60–10, AEG 80–20, AEG 80–60) continued as *Geschäftsbereich Automatisierungstechnik* (after 1980 as ATM Computer).
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1975 the former Telefunken Headquarter at Berlin-Charlottenburg, Ernst-Reuter-Platz 7 was sold.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The building had been previously rented to Technische Universität Berlin.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1976, to circumvent the requirement of equal participation of employees in the supervisory board, Dr.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Walter Cipa (Dipl.-Geol.) (AEG boss from 1976 to 1980) created four further companies as wholly owned joint stock companies in addition to the two household appliance companies.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1979 Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft AEG-Telefunken was renamed AEG-Telefunken by dropping the supplement "Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft", used since 1887.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In February 1980, Heinz Dürr became board Chairman (until 1990).
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In August 1982 a restructuring plan, backed with federal guarantees of 600 million DM and new bank loans of 275 million DM, fell apart at the first disagreement between the banks.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] A banking consortium provided an administrative loan of DM 1.1 billion to the AEG Group until June 1983; 400 million of which only to be available on a guarantee by the federal government.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Not only was AEG-Telefunken affected, but also its subsidiaries Küppersbusch in Gelsenkirchen, Hermann Zanker Maschinenfabrik in Tübingen and Carl Neff in Bretten.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The Alno-Möbelwerke in Pfullendorf was taken over by the minority shareholders, and separated from the group.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The suppliers to AEG were affected and some filed for bankruptcy—including Becher & Co.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Möbelfabriken in Bühlertann—with lack of continuity of company policy a factor.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The site at Brunnenstraße in the former Berlin district of Wedding was also sold, as were the firms AEG-Fabrik Essen and Bauknecht.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG played an important role in the history of the German railways; the company was involved in the development and manufacture of the electrical parts of almost all German electric locomotive series and contributed to the introduction of electrical power in German railways.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Additionally many steam locomotives were made in AEG factories.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1931 the company acquired Borsig and transferred the locomotive production to the AEG-Borsig works (Borsig Lokomotiv-Werke) from the Borsig plant in Tegel.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In 1948 the plant became VEB Lokomotivbau Elektrotechnische Werke.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] In addition to numerous electric locomotives produced for the DR steam locomotive production continued until 1954.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] When the Federal Republic of Germany began implementing AC propulsion systems AEG found itself in competition with Brown, Boveri & Cie.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The prototype DB Class E320 was built with Krupp as dual voltage (15 kV and 25 kV AC) test machine, the technology ultimately leading to locomotives such as DB Class 120 and ICE 1.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Only after German reunification and the adoption of the LEW plant in Hennigsdorf did AEG's name return to whole locomotive manufacturing, but only for a short time.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] "AEG locomotives" became part of ABB Daimler-Benz Transportation (later ADtranz) and currently the technology developed in the past, in part, now enables Alstom to build the very successful Traxx series of locomotives.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] Between 1992 to 1994, AEG built 96 metro cars for Shanghai Metro.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG manufactured a range of aircraft from 1912 to 1918.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The first aircraft in 1912 was of wooden construction and modeled after the Wright brothers biplane.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] It had a wingspan of 17.5 m (57 ft 5 in); was powered by an eight-cylinder engine producing 75 hp; unloaded weight was 850 kg; and could attain a speed of 65 km/h (40 mph).
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] From 1912, the construction of airplanes proceeded in mixed wood and steel tube construction with fabric covering.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] One of the planes designed and built was a *Riesenflugzeug* ("giant aircraft") AEG R.I.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] This aircraft was powered by four 260 hp (190 kW) Mercedes D.IVa engines linked to a combination leather cone and dog clutch.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The first flight tests were satisfactory, but on 3 September 1918, the R.I broke up in the air killing its seven crewmen.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The most successful in terms of production figures of all the AEG aircraft designs was that of the G.IV *Grossflugzeuge* ("large aircraft") heavy tactical bomber, of which one still survives of the 320 built, as the sole surviving World War One German multi-engine bomber.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] During the Second World War AEG produced machines for reconnaissance purposes, including a helicopter platform driven by an AC motor.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] This was a tethered craft that could not fly freely; the power supply was carried by three cables from the ground.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] The machine reached an altitude of 300 m.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG bought Kühlstein in 1902, founding the division *Neue Automobil Gesellschaft* (New Automobile Company), to make cars.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-german-company] AEG withdrew from car production in 1908.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] The **AEG R.I** was a prototype biplane heavy bomber (*Riesenflugzeug*) aircraft built by the *Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft* (AEG) during the First World War for the Imperial German Army's (*Deutsches Heer*) Imperial German Air Service (*Luftstreitkräfte*).
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] It made its first flight in mid-1918 and only one of the eight aircraft ordered was completed.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] That aircraft disintegrated in flight with the loss of all aboard shortly before the end of the war in November.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] AEG received an order in late 1916 from the Inspectorate of Flying Troops (*Inspektion der Fliegertruppen* (*Idflieg*) for a pair of heavy bombers in its (*Riesenflugzeug*) program.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] These were four-engined aircraft with the engines located inside the fuselage to allow in-flight maintenance.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] The R.I's 260-horsepower (190 kW) Mercedes D.IVa straight-six engines drove the propellers via a complex system of gearboxes and driveshafts so that any engine could power any propeller.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] The propellers were mounted in nacelles between the wings that contained their gearboxes.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] The engines were initially equipped with individual radiators mounted on the sides of the fuselage, but these were replaced by four radiators mounted on the rear central struts.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] The engines were grouped together in an engine room immediately behind the nose observer's compartment in the nose.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] The fuselage was built in AEG's normal manner from cable-braced steel tubing.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] From the nose to the end of the engine compartment the fuselage was covered in plywood, but doped fabric was used over the rest.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] The three-bay wings were built from a pair of steel tube spars with duraluminium ribs.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] The R.I made its first flight on 14 June 1918.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] Initial flights demonstrated that the aircraft was tail-heavy and that the engine cooling and rudder area were insufficient, but modifications were quickly made and the flight testing resumed.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] On 3 September 1918, a newly assembled propeller, which had not been given sufficient time for glue to cure, disintegrated, which allowed its driveshaft to damage the fuselage which caused the R.I to break up, killing all seven crew on board.
[src:aeg-german-company/aeg-r-i] Of the seven further AEG R.1 aircraft planned or under production when the war ended, only one aircraft was even partially complete.
